<TEXT>
china is the worlds largest wheat producer 
but is not keeping pace with its own consumer demand for more 
bread noodles and dumplings 
as a result china has been buying huge amounts of wheat from 
other countries including the united states an agriculture 
department analyst says import demand will continue to grow at 
least through the turn of the century 
even though it is the worlds largest producer of wheat 
chinas domestic demand exceeds supplies says frederick w crook 
of the departments economic research service wheat output has 
risen steadily as farmers have boosted yields because of greater 
irrigation and use of improved varieties 
crook in a report on chinas wheat economy said population 
growth and consumer preference for wheat products such as 
noodles steamed dumplings bread and pastries have spurred demand 
as the worlds most populous country with 11 billion people 
even slight changes in per capita use can translate into large 
numbers 
crook said per capita wheat consumption rose steadily from 29 
kilograms in 1960 to 48 kilos in 1978 then as supplies increased 
because of import and production gains the average jumped to 90 
kilograms per person in 1987 
a kilogram is about 22 pounds ninety kilos would be about 198 
pounds or approximately 33 bushels of wheat allowing 60 pounds 
per bushel 
china has been at peaks and valleys as a customer of us wheat 
farmers since the early 1970s lately beijing has been a large and 
consistent buyer of us wheat rivaling the soviet union at times 
in the 198889 wheat marketing year that ran through last may 
31 china imported almost 81 million metric tons of us wheat and 
became the largest foreign customer of american growers the soviet 
union by comparison imported 496 million tons in the same period 
so far in 198990 china has bought about 47 million tons 
against the soviet unions purchases as of dec 14 of less than 2 
million tons 
a metric ton the unit favored in world grain trade is about 
2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels of wheat it also is 
equal to 1000 kilograms 
both china and the soviet union have bought large amounts of 
wheat under a us price subsidy arrangement the export 
enhancement program under eep private exporters can sell to 
designated foreign countries at reduced prices and then collect 
usdaowned commodities as bonuses or subsidies to make up the 
price difference 
from a production standpoint china has been the worlds largest 
wheat producer in four of the last five years according to usda 
statistics 
chinas wheat output this year for example is estimated at 91 
million tons compared with 89 million for the soviet union and 
556 million for the united states 
other major producers this year include canada 244 million 
tons australia 125 million argentina 107 million india 53 
million eastern europe 423 million and the european economic 
community 793 million 
crook said that by world standards china has achieved fairly 
high wheat yields and is surpassing those in india pakistan and 
countries which have large areas of nonirrigated wheat such as 
canada australia the soviet union and the united states 
on the other hand crook said wheat yields are higher in mexico 
france poland and japan 
crook said that chinese experts predict wheat yields will climb 
an average of about 165 percent a year and that by the year 2000 
there will be some decrease in total wheat area but they claim 
that total output by then will increase to between 100 million and 
105 million tons 
chinas population will continue to grow in the next decade 
and if per capita income continues to rise demand for wheat will 
also increase crook said however prospects for rapid gains 
in domestic wheat output are dim because little arable land can 
be shifted to wheat production and yields are already high 
as a result he added the outlook for wheat exports to china 
looks promising in the near future but the rate of growth will 
depend mostly on the ability of the rest of chinas economy to earn 
foreign exchange 
</TEXT>
