the government of king hussein on tuesday 
removed most categories of crimes from the military courts 
significantly easing jordans 22yearold martial law 
state jordan television said the cabinet acting on the wishes 
of hussein gave civil courts jurisdiction over cases ranging from 
political offenses to price hike violations and homicide 
the action is the last in a series of liberalizing measures in 
the kingdom which this year held its first general elections in 
more than two decades and reversed a controversial 1988 law that 
nationalized all daily newspapers 
the changes were sparked by four days of rioting in april in 
which at least 10 people died following price hikes of many 
subsidized goods and services and the appearance of government 
indifference to the economic situation of many jordanians 
the cabinet said civil courts will immediately start handling 
cases involving firearms gunplay at weddings homicide price 
gouging forgery assaults on officials violations of martial law 
orders and the ban on membership in political parties as well as 
the law against communism 
military courts have handled such cases since martial law was 
imposed during the 1967 arabisraeli war in which jordan lost the 
west bank with much of its economy and population to israel 
the cabinet also said that a ministerial committee will study 
whether to remove economic and security offenses from martial law 
jurisdiction and will report its findings within two months 
the action comes the same week that the newly appointed 
government of prime minister mudar badran must by law seek a vote 
of confidence from the recently elected parliament most of whose 
members campaigned for an end to martial law 
the king earlier this year promised to limit martial law 
