<TEXT>
securities and exchange commission chairman 
richard c breeden on tuesday selected agency veteran william c 
mclucas as the secs new head of enforcement and announced creation 
of a new fraud unit covering the sale of securities by financial 
institutions 
mclucas 39 will succeed gary lynch who resigned as sec 
director of enforcement in july after heading some of the agencys 
biggest insider trading investigations 
the enforcement job which does not require senate confirmation 
is considered the second most powerful position at the sec and it 
is breedens first major appointment since president bush tapped 
him as chairman last summer 
mclucas who has worked in the enforcement division for the past 
12 years had been considered one of the frontrunners for the 
post but breeden said he had considered three other sec attorneys 
and several persons from outside the agency before making the final 
selection 
breeden said the sec had decided to create a 25attorney special 
unit to investigate overly aggressive sales of securities by 
savings and loans and other financial institutions 
such sales have been a major focus of congressional hearings 
into the activities at lincoln savings and loan association the 
irvine califbased sampl whose failure is expected to be the 
biggest in us history costing taxpayers as much as 2 billion 
lincoln savings parent company is american continental corp 
headed by arizona businessman charles h keating jr when american 
continental filed for protection under the bankruptcy laws it left 
shareholders and investors holding nearly worthless stocks and 
bonds 
included in this group were some 22000 small investors who 
purchased nearly 200 million in corporate bonds at lincolns 29 
southern california branches about twothirds of these investors 
were elderly depositors at congressionaly hearings some of these 
investors testified that they wrongly believed that the bonds they 
were purchasing were federally insured 
breeden said that the new sec unit would try to prevent other 
financially troubled sampls from turning to fradulent practices in a 
desperate effort to raise cash 
we intend to see to it that when people are sold securities 
they are provided all the necessary information breeden said 
lynch who resigned to join a new york law firm received 
widespread praise for a series of big insider trading cases 
beginning with the exposure of stockbroker dennis levine lynch 
also spearheaded cases that resulted in a 100 million settlement 
with speculator ivan boesky and a record 650 million settlement of 
a massive civil fraud cause with junk bondgiant drexel burnham 
lambert inc 
in may 1986 the sec filed charges against levine whose 
cooperation led to boesky who in turn implicated drexel burnham in 
the largest securities fraud case ever brought by the government 
lynch took over the enforcement division in 1985 at a time of 
turmoil after his predecessor john fedders stepped down amid 
allegations that he beat his wife 
lynch was credited with restoring morale at the agency the 
scandals in recent years have forced wall streets big brokerage 
houses to reevaluate their compliance and ethics codes and led 
congress to increase the penalties for insider trading 
at the news conference breeden noted that congress has boosted 
the sec budget by almost 20 percent this year to 168 million 
providing enough new money to hire an additional 100 lawyers 
he said it was important for the sec to police the securities 
industry in such a way that individual investors will have renewed 
confidence individual investors have left the market in droves in 
recent years partly out of fears raised by the huge gyrations in 
stock prices that occurred in october of 1987 and 1989 
during the 1970s the secs enforcement division first gained 
attention under stanley sporkin for pursuing corporations that 
maintained political slush funds and paid bribes to win overseas 
business 
</TEXT>
