men after being tipped off by an informant said us army lt col 
william leszczynski commander of the 3rd battalion 9th infantry 
regiment 
authorities reported finding rifles shotguns handguns and much 
ammunition as well as cocaine marijuana morphine and drug 
paraphernalia 
torture apparently was carried out in the same building 
leszczynski said his troops found electronic devices that could 
be hooked up to people for electric shocks 
they found a room filled with immigration files of foreigners 
from more than two dozen countries including cuba nicaragua and 
colombia the files in racks that reached the ceiling contained 
detailed information on foreigners entries and exits each file 
had a small photo of the subject 
one miamibased agent of the us drug enforcement 
administration who visited the white stucco house tuesday said that 
at first glance it seemed to be a legitimate antinarcotics 
operation 
what i find unusual is that these files were kept in a 
house she said i need to find out whose house this is in 
whose name its registered she spoke on condition of anonymity 
the files largely were from the 1960s through the 70s 
its good for us the agent said this tells me whos been 
in an out of the country i already found some files of colombian 
drug traffickers so now i know they were here now i go for the 
more recent files 
she would not say how many dea agents came here although she 
said it was far fewer than 20 the us military has provided 
transport communications and other support she added 
three makeshift jails at the back of the house seemed to have 
been inhabited recently a plastic container with urine stood in 
the corner of one cell where the occupant had slept on a dirty mat 
and cardboard placed on the cement floor 
