the sri lankan army monday in northeastern nidamwela town and were 
brought to a makeshift detention center 30 miles away military 
officials said 
they surrendered a few hours after guerrillas of the liberation 
tigers of tamil eelam attacked a tamil national army camp killing 
44 militants in the batticaloa district the officials said on 
condition of anonymity 
the tigers the strongest guerrilla group in sri lankas tamil 
ethnic minority have intensified their power struggle with rival 
tamil militants as indian peacekeeping troops wind down their 
2year effort to pacify the northeastern part of the island 
the tigers and the sri lankan government claim the departing 
indians have armed and trained 4000 members of the tamil national 
army india has repeatedly insisted it only trained a volunteer 
force sanctioned by the sri lankan government and not the tamil 
national army which has been outlawed by president ranasinghe 
premadasas government 
indian troops started arriving in sri lanka july 30 1987 under 
an accord with india in an effort to settle the insurrection but 
the tigers reneged on the accord and attacked the indians who were 
supposed to oversee a surrender of arms 
india agreed in september to withdraw its last troops by dec 31 
but later said it was unlikely to meet that deadline an estimated 
25000 indian soldiers remain 
tamils who make up 18 percent of the islands 16 million 
people claim discrimination by the majority sinhalese and tamil 
militants want a separate homeland the revolt has claimed 11000 
lives since it started in 1983 
the 155 militants had slipped out of the camp friday in search 
