<TEXT>
several thousand people at jerusalems western 
wall celebrated hanukkah tuesday via satellite with jews in new 
york moscow london and paris 
the mostly ultraorthodox crowd watched quietly as prayers were 
chanted and the fifth candle was lighted in all five cities in the 
first hightech global hannukah ceremony 
hannukah the eightday festival of lights celebrates the 
victory of the jews over the grecosyrian kingdom in 165 bc the 
kingdom tried to impose its culture on the jews and desecrated the 
holy temple in jerusalem with statues of greek gods 
according to legend when the jews entered jerusalem and tried 
to rekindle the temples eternal flame they found enough oil for 
one day but the oil miraculously lasted eight days 
to commemorate the miracle jews light candles at sunset for 
eight consecutive days 
the western wall where the candlelighting ceremony was held 
is the sole remnant of the second jewish temple and the holiest 
site in judaism 
ruth kabakoff a 60yearold tourist from orlando fla watched 
one of two screens facing the western wall with excitement she 
said she heard about the satellite ceremony in her hotel from 
announcements in the streets over loudspeakers 
i think it is wonderful that jews feel that strongly about 
their faith to join together it makes me want to cry she said 
