<TEXT>
perhaps no decade this century has begun amid 
greater economic unpheaval challenge and potential than the 1990s 
and it isnt due solely to the fall of communist regimes in eastern 
europe 
western europe too is in the midst of historic changes scheduled 
to begin in little more than a year with integration of the 
european economic community japan is facing adjustments because of 
competition 
the american challenge is as big as any of them it must 
solidify the great accomplishments of the 1980s bring down 
inflation steer the way through an economic downturn reduce the 
trade deficit and balance budgets 
japan which ascended to economic dominance in many trade areas 
during the 1980s is faced with demands to make its economy more 
receptive to imports to reduce its trade surplus and perhaps to 
develop its infrastructure 
china is trying to lift itself to world economic standards in 
the production of goods hong kong faces a change of sponsorship 
from britain to china taiwan south korea singapore and other 
small asian nations face the challenge of remaining competitive 
while lifting living standards 
confronted with evidence of superior lifestyles in more highly 
developed countries much of africa latin america and the mideast 
are in political and economic ferment that no longer can be 
repressed 
amid the confusion there are few blueprints for the future so 
carefully defined as that of the european economic community there 
is no clear procedure for turning centrally planned economies into 
market economies 
nor is there time to develop plans instant communication 
produces instant change but contributes little toward identifying 
programs for carrying out the changes the demands for change are 
swift the implementation remains slow 
through all of the changes however there is at least one 
constant factor opportunity 
for major trading nations it means new markets for 
underdeveloped nations it means the chance to radically lift 
depressed living standards for all nations it means a more 
productive allocation of resources and skills 
managed well the changes could be a great leap forward for the 
world community prospects for western europe for example already 
had brightened with the scheduled removal of trade barriers among 
12 nations in 1992 
now says albert cox jr economic analyst with the investment 
counseling firm bil trainer wortham inc there is the 
possibility of massive growth in international trade in the next 10 
years 
if that happens he concludes history tells us that greatly 
enhanced world economic prosperity will be the end result 
no matter what economic changes occur throughout the world they 
are bound to have an impact on domestic politics and economic 
direction within the united states 
already washington is debating the possibilities of the 
socalled peace dividend or billions of dollars in funds that 
supposedly will be available as a result of a cutback in defense 
programs but that is only the beginning 
if the worlds experimentation with market economies continues 
it will provide a showcase for those seeking to direct the american 
economy toward the most efficient ends 
conceivably it could even mean an approach to that longsought 
american goal of shrinking the federal government while maintaining 
and even improving services to the public 
</TEXT>
