<TEXT>
west europeans are looking anxiously eastward as 
they plunge ahead with elaborate plans for the 1990s in a climate 
changing so quickly that answers are coming faster than questions 
their grand design is a single europe of 12 economic 
community members starting at the end of 1992 a melting away of 
internal barriers and a blending of policies under the umbrella of 
the north atlantic treaty organization 
but after the berlin wall crumbled and as a 44yearold iron 
curtain buckles everything from the pace of integration to the 
overall strategy has been thrown into doubt 
some europeans suspect that against soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachevs image of a common european home the smaller 
single europe structure is a shaky house of cards 
nato is under mounting pressure to stand down in the face of 
former enemies who are now acting like friends 
the official view stressed at a european community summit at 
strasbourg in december is that a united western europe is crucial 
to helping eastern europe 
ec leaders moved closer to a central bank a common currency and 
uniform social benefits they also agreed to set up a bank of 
europe to help newly democratic eastern neighbors 
the ec called for a flexibility yet to be defined and most of 
its leaders applauded washingtons plans to support a stronger ec 
and to broaden nato into a political forum for solving problems 
us secretary of state james a baker iii speaking on a visit 
to berlin in december suggested a greater dialogue with the east 
not only on european problems but also to ease tensions elsewhere 
in the world 
as europe changes the instruments for western cooperation 
must adapt he said working together we must design and 
gradually put into place a new architecture for a new era 
whatever shape a new europe takes its leaders agree the 
cornerstone will be germany in many ways the divided nation has 
already united much hangs on how this union is formalized 
germany would grow from a reasonably sized ec partner to a 
colossus of 80 million inhabitants with a gross national product of 
14 trillion approaching the soviet unions 
without a separate east germany the soviet unions warsaw pact 
military alliance is reduced to a few satellites that are fast 
slipping away 
foreign minister hans dietrich genscher of west germany insists 
that a reunited germany would demilitarize europe and draw the 
soviet union and other eastern european countries closer to the ec 
but president francois mitterrand of france maintains it is too 
early to predict the direction europe now will take 
france clearly prefers separate germanys while publicly 
supporting the germans right to settle the issue themselves 
french leaders expect moscow to block any formal reunification 
other ec partners while encouraging the lightningfast changes 
take a similar stance for varying reasons 
spain portugal and greece fear investment and development funds 
they counted on will be diverted to the east italy argues that 
postwar borders should remain intact 
britain which has resisted ec monetary and social integration 
may find an ally in a west germany anxious to preserve some 
independence within a single europe 
but prime minister margaret thatcher after an emergency summit 
in november made it plain that britain was not anxious for a rapid 
blurring of eastwest lines in germany 
all military matters must continue to be conducted through 
nato and the warsaw pact she said at a time of great change 
its necessary to keep the background of stability and security 
in west germany reunification is already a dominant issue in 
general elections still a year off 
chancellor helmut kohl has thrown open the door and encouraged 
investment to speed unification in bonn west german officials 
already refer to the eastern part of the country 
if kohls centerright coalition stays in power it will have a 
mandate to push reunification in such circumstances kohl is 
likely to have reluctant support from mitterrand among others 
in broad terms western europes mood is buoyant the 
organization for economic cooperation and development estimates put 
growth at 27 percent for 1991 higher than in the united states 
the soviet union would like a share of that prosperity some 
officials say the soviets now prefer trade to domination in europe 
on dec 18 the soviet union and the ec signed a 10year trade 
pact opening the way for a larger western role in a changing 
soviet economy 
foreign minister eduard shevardnadze remarked this is a 
result of a gigantic effort made by the peoples of europe to 
overcome political and military confrontation to overcome the 
economic division of our continent 
in short he said the cold war is over 
</TEXT>
