<TEXT>
the idyllic south pacific saw its first 
coups political violence and secessionist battles in the 1980s 
but in the decade ahead the century of the pacific beckons and 
the island states expect to have a small but assertive voice in the 
world 
speaking in unison across a vast expanse of water will be the 
voices of a new generation of postcolonial leaders with 
intractible problems malnutrition fragile economies with scant 
export prospects and urban unemployment brought on by villagers 
flocking to towns with increased expectations 
one of the continuing difficulties of the small island states 
is that many will remain dependent on foreign aid and in some 
respects more in the past as they continue to grapple with these 
problems said an australian government offiical 
the decade of the 1980s saw unprecented turmoil in the region 
fiji had two racially inspired military coups civil lawlessness 
in papua new guinea claimed more than 50 lives the capitals of 
vanuatu and french polynesia suffered destructive rioting 
hostagetaking in new caledonia triggered a bloody french assault 
added to that was a perceived soviet military threat to the 
region concern about moscows growing economic inroads and anxiety 
that libya was making a foothold in an area better known for its 
tranquility and palmfringed lagoons than as a political hothouse 
covering 22 percent of the worlds surface the south pacific is 
home to 5 million people excluding australia and new zealand 
environmental problems like depletion of the ozone layer over 
antarctica and the earths global warming has caused serious 
concern in a region of lowlying atolls that could be swamped by 
seas swollen by melting polar ice 
the future of antarctica is assured a big debate as countries 
like australia push for protected wilderness status against others 
who view the worlds last great wilderness as a minerals treasure 
house 
if for nothing else that will happen because of the sheer 
importance of antarctica in regard to the worlds weather 
patterns said the australian official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
driftnet fishing the casting of huge nets over a large area of 
the sea to scoop up tons of fish at once was a problem virtually 
unheard of six months ago but it moved into world forums after 
island governments banded together to draw up an international 
convention and propose united nations resolutions that forced japan 
and taiwan to scale down the practice 
the 1980s gave birth to an antinuclear new zealand and the 
declaration of a south pacific nuclear free zone adopted by 15 
island states 
they are increasingly becoming very effective in articulating 
their point of view and building up cooperation among member 
states said the australian official 
it is a small but growing voice helped by a new generation of 
more assertive leaders 
against that he said there are no new bonanzas looming that 
are going to provide them with any riches 
the concept of the century of the pacific took a first 
tentative step in 1989 when 12 major pacific rim countries 
including the united states met in canberra australia to plan 
the future 
they agreed to meet again in singapore in early 1990 and 
probably again in bangkok thailand later in the year to plan an 
asianpacific cooperative venture an idea all agreed was one 
whose time has come 
the canberra meeting brought together us secretary of state 
james a baker iii with his counterparts from japan south korea 
australia new zealand thailand singapore malaysia the 
philippines brunei canada and indonesia they represented 19 
billion people and 280 billion in transpacific trade 50 percent 
more than transatlantic trade 
the meeting was described by us state department officials as 
the most important economic initiative in 50 years 
