<TEXT>
having struggled through a lost 
decade of crushing debt and economic stagnation south america 
limps into the 1990s with the grim prospect of more tough times 
its many young democracies still fight to establish firm roots 
in troubled societies inherited in many cases from nowretired 
military governments 
at the same time they face the daunting challenge of halting a 
continental slide deeper into underdevelopment 
the 1980s began with what is now generically known as the 
crisis plunging prices for south americas products accompanied 
by skyrocketing foreign debts 
the decade ended with those debts approaching 300 billion 
overall with surreal inflation averaging nearly 1000 percent a 
year with spreading poverty and with widespread social unrest at 
the close of the decade per capita production was 8 percent less 
than it was at the start 
the troubles struck not only in countries with a tradition of 
political and social commotion such as peru and argentina even 
longsteady venezuela was jolted by price riots in 1989 colombia 
another economic and political stalwart waged bloody war with a 
billiondollar cocaine underworld that was deeply entrenched in 
several other south american countries 
the experts see few signs of a better decade ahead 
as far as perspectives for the 1990s there is a certain 
temptation to predict that the crisis will continue said gert 
rosenthal director of the united nations economic commission for 
latin america and the caribbean 
in an interview in santiago rosenthal said there were grounds 
for pessimism in the inertia of latin americas deep and 
longlasting recession which has prompted him to call the 1980s 
a lost decade 
he said he also harbored the suspicion that the prolonged 
expansion of world development cant last much longer and any 
recession in the international economy surely will hit latin 
america very hard 
in addition he noted theres little prospect of badly needed 
fresh credit for the debtor countries trying to refinance loans 
that drain the region each year of 30 billion money that could be 
put to use at home 
nonetheless rosenthal cited several positive developments that 
could help in coping with the future 
he said south america learned a hard lesson in the 1980s its 
archaic economies run by creaky state bureaucracies must be 
overhauled if it is to compete in the world marketplace also he 
said both creditor banks and debtor countries were adopting 
evermore flexible positions on foreign debts 
he also cited a certain revitalization of the old battered 
concept of latin american cooperation and integration 
the 1980s began with nine of the continents 12 countries 
controlled by authoritarian military governments the decade ends 
with elected leaders governing all but in chile where elections in 
december set the stage for the first civilian government since 1973 
few of those new civilian governments have shown any success in 
solving economic problems but none has yet to fall indeed while 
particular governments have sometimes suffered from slumping 
popular support surveys indicate little inclination for the return 
of military rule periodic uprisings at argentine garrisons have 
been quickly snuffed 
despite the entire decades critical economic situation it 
appears clear that the democratic regimes are becoming consolidated 
in the principal countries said jose joaquin brunner director 
of the independent latin american faculty of social sciences 
there is no reason to believe the democratic processes will 
be interrupted in the foreseeable future brunner said even 
where the situation is most precarious such as peru the 
institutional machine keeps working despite everything 
the wave of democracy has produced a spirit of fellowship and 
cooperation reflected in numerous summit meetings among south 
american nations involving as many as a halfdozen presidents 
brunner said a new political and economic coherence is emerging 
everyone sees the need for relatively pragmatic programs 
aimed at economic restructuring he said no one is turning to 
ideological alternatives there is no south american wave in favor 
of socialism for instance 
in deeply indebted brazil a probusiness conservative fernando 
collor de mello edged out a socialist luis inacio lula da silva 
in presidential elections dec 17 
brunner said deep ideological divisions and animosities that 
often fractured south american societies are being erased 
the range of possibilities has become so narrow its obliging 
everyone to be pragmatic he said 
