<TEXT>
the caribbean which comprises some 
of the worlds poorest and most heavily indebted nations faces the 
prospect of increasing economic and social pressures in the 1990s 
problems confronting the two dozen island states south of 
florida range from rising unemployment and shrinking markets for 
sugar and bananas to the spread of aids and drug trafficking 
some analysts believe the strain could be severe enough to 
produce a resurgence of radical politics and civil unrest 
there is just no way for stable democracy to continue in these 
islands unless more jobs and income are generated said john 
collins adviser on the caribbean for gov rafael hernandez colon 
of puerto rico 
while celebrating the 500th anniversary of colombus discovery 
of the new world in 1992 the caribbean will likely find itself 
still coping with the effects of events dictated far from its 
shores 
caribbean leaders have expressed concern for example that the 
cold war thaw could divert western investment from their region to 
the nations emerging from communist domination in eastern europe 
likewise cuba could be forced to reduce its economic dependence 
on the soviet bloc said norman girvan of jamaica president of the 
association of caribbean economists 
whats happening in western europe is changing our external 
environment he said whats happening in eastern europe must 
change the environment of cuba 
for much of the region one of the darkest clouds on the horizon 
is the proposed single european market after 1992 a unified market 
would lift trade barriers within the 12nation european economic 
community and harmonize foreign trade agreements 
among the nations most at risk are the windward islands of 
dominica st lucia st vincent and grenada which together ship 
240000 tons of bananas a year to britain after 1992 they could 
lose preferential access to the british market and face fierce 
competition from more efficient banana producers elsewhere 
many also fear the loss of benefits as a result of the new 
uscanadian trade accord and proposed changes in the caribbean 
basin initiative the program set up by the reagan administration 
to promote usoriented economic and political development in the 
caribbean and central america 
the next decade is going to test the very theory that 
microstates can survive in a world increasingly dominated by 
massive trading blocs said larry birns director of the 
washingtonbased council on hemispheric affairs 
propects for the sugar industry meanwhile are dimmed by years 
of sharply declining us import quotas low world prices and 
increasing reliance on corn sweeteners and us and european sugar 
beets 
compton bourne professor of economics at the university of the 
west indies in trinidad said he thought pressure would build on 
caribbean governments to follow through on commitments to integrate 
their economies and pool limited resources 
but he said propects for the 1990s largely depended on the 
willingness of developed nations to reduce the regions debt burden 
and provide sorely needed investment 
analysts said the expected loss of revenue from traditional 
exports would probably accelerate a move into tourism already the 
no 1 earner of foreign exchange for several islands and enhance 
such industries as computer data entry that use cheap semiskilled 
labor 
birns said there was a danger that environmental considerations 
will be overwhelmed by the rush to exploit the islands lucrative 
tourism potential tourism is also regarded as a significant factor 
in the rapid spread of aids prostitution and drug use throughout 
the caribbean 
although conservative prous governments dominate the region 
birns said the approaching crisis could give rise to radically 
leftist leadership and possible destabilization 
if western lending institutions such as the international 
monetary fund and the world bank force further economic austerity 
on such debtridden nations as guyana jamaica and trinidad 
youre going to see an increasingly dangerous situation birns 
said 
he added that the caribbean of the 1990s would figure more 
prominently in us policy because of increased immigration and 
closer scrutiny of the regions role as a major drugtrafficking 
route and source of moneylaundering through offshore banks 
haiti the caribbeans perennial trouble spot approaches the 
new decade at a political crossroads 
opinion is divided over whether haitis military leader lt 
gen prosper avril will fulfill his pledge to turn over power to a 
civilian government in elections scheduled for the fall of 1990 no 
one expects a swift solution to the countrys profound economic 
problems 
