<TEXT>
bedeviled by wars corruption 
mismanagement and a burgeoning population africa is ending a 
decade of economic decline and facing what some experts say could 
be a nightmare scenario in the 1990s 
the nightmare increased hunger disease poverty and conflict 
on a continent already desperately poor and largely unable to 
survive on its own without huge doses of foreign aid 
while warning of possible new violence elsewhere many observers 
predict an end to war in the coming decade in mozambique ethiopia 
sudan and other embattled african countries as combatants fight to 
stalemate and exhaustion 
namibia ended the 1980s with an election for a constitutional 
assembly and will enter the world of independent nations in the 
coming year peace also seems close at hand in neighboring angola 
whiteruled south africa which has long meddled in both those 
countries appears to be changing its racial policies albeit too 
slowly for some 
but with the exception of south africa the possibility of 
greater stability in those countries will not automatically bring 
prosperity to them or to the vast continent as a whole say 
economists for the world bank and other institutions 
the 46 countries of subsaharan africa a region of 450 million 
people that includes all of the continents nations except morocco 
algeria tunisia libya egypt and south africa had a combined 
gross domestic product in 1987 of about 135 billion 
that was about the same as belgium with a population of only 10 
million 
that comparison as well as any illustrates the depths of 
poverty from which most african nations are struggling to emerge 
only in many cases to slip deeper and deeperinto debt and 
deprivation 
the world bank in a study that took nearly three years to 
complete and was released in late november says there is a 
solution for africa one that depends largely on africans 
themselves and calls for a sharp reversal of past practices 
the bank a leading multinational lending institution blames 
many of africas problems on corruption poor government marked by 
bureaucratic bungling and misguided economic practices rooted in 
marxistleninist theory all that it said must end 
it was perhaps the bluntest assessment the bank has ever made of 
any of the worlds economies but it may have been far easier and 
faster to write than the suggested changes will be coming to a 
continent whose rulers have too often equated power with plunder 
the world bank and others have also stressed the need for a 
sharp reduction in africas birth rate at 32 percent it is the 
highest ever seen anywhere in the world and one that inexorably 
accelerates pressures for land food and jobs and threatens new 
internal and crossborder conflicts 
the population of subsaharan africa in 1965 was only half the 
450 million it is now and if current trends continue it will double 
again to 1 billion in 20 years the world bank estimates that even 
if fertility fell tomorrow to two children for each african family 
the continents population would continue to grow for the next 60 
to 70 years 
no region of the world has ever managed to develop with so 
high a rate of population growth the bank said 
even in those countries where peace has arrived or is on the 
horizon it is likely to take most of the new decade to revive 
their warshattered economies given optimum circumstances some 
have fallen not just 10 years behind in the development process 
but 20 or 30 
the world banks prescription for africa called for increased 
aid of about 4 percent a year through the 1990s from the developed 
nations but many african politicians and planners worry that the 
east european countries emerging from behind the iron curtain 
poland hungary czechoslovakia east germany and possibly others 
will siphon off aid dollars as they attempt to restructure their 
economies with western help 
as if those problems werent enough a new peril arose in the 
1980s that threatens africa in the coming years with a catastrophe 
comparable to the droughts and famines that periodically sweep the 
continent 
it is aids 
health authorities estimate that 15 million to 2 million 
africans mostly young adults will die of aids in the 1990s 
draining even further the continents already shallow pool of 
skilled workers and forcing many countries to spend more scarce 
money on medical services 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

