<TEXT>
t franklin williams a geriatrics physician is 
director of the national institute on aging one of the 13 
institutes that comprise the national institutes of health of the 
department of health and human services 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the speed with which society has responded 
to the aids epidemic is heartening yet there is one group that 
society has not begun to attend to in terms of its risk older 
americans 
the fact is 10 percent of all reported cases of acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome have involved people aged 50 and over and more 
older people are believed to be infected although not yet 
experiencing symptoms 
with increased age comes a decline in immune system functions 
making older people more susceptible to a variety of illnesses such 
as cancers and infections because of these changes in immune 
function aids may affect older people differently than it does the 
young data from the centers for disease control suggests that most 
older people infected with the aids virus have developed disease 
symptoms more quickly than younger patients 
the older population also receives the highest rate of blood 
transfusions blood banks now assure safer blood products than 
before 1985 when the public blood supply was not yet being 
screened for the virus by then however many older people had 
already been exposed to possibly contaminated transfusions as a 
result blood transfusions are the second most common cause of aids 
in people over 50 after sexual contact moreover no one knows 
how many people received infected blood and are now unknowingly 
infecting spouses or sexual partners 
older aids patients who have early symptoms also risk going 
undiagnosed because early symptoms of aids such as fatigue loss 
of appetite and swollen glands are similar to other more common 
illnesses many people including health professionals may 
dismiss them as minor ailments 
medical experts predict that a cure or vaccine against aids is 
not likely to be found in the near future so preventing the spread 
of aids will very much depend on behavioral changes such as using 
condoms when sexually involved with someone other than a mutually 
faithful uninfected partner 
prevention also begins with education aids is not spread by 
casual contact but rather through sexual relations use of 
infected needles and blood transfusions reliable uptodate 
information is available from many sources the public health 
service sent a brochure understanding aids to every home in 
the country call the national aids hotline 1800342aids for 
another copy other hotlines also can answer specific questions 
researchers are working to understand aids and how to treat 
people who are infected treatment for the symptoms usually 
involves some drug therapy such as azt azidothymidine which 
currently is being used in many patients to prolong life other 
promising drugs are also being tested 
people exposed to the virus should stay in touch with a doctor 
who is wellinformed about the latest research for help finding an 
expert call a medical schools infectious disease department or 
the national aids hotline 
you can make a valuable contribution by offering to help groups 
in your community who work with aids patients many operate on a 
shoestring and depend heavily on individual contributions of time 
and money these groups include the american red cross march of 
dimes boys clubs and girls clubs and the local ymca their phone 
numbers are listed in your directory and they will be glad to tell 
you how to get involved with education fundraising drives or 
volunteer programs 
in the years ahead individuals willing to offer their services 
to aids patients will be increasingly needed volunteers can 
contribute a great deal without endangering their health for 
example as people with aids become more disabled they have 
trouble meeting their daily needs they appreciate help with 
shopping cooking meals or just regular visits for talking 
for more information on volunteer programs call your health 
department or the national aids hotline 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the following local and national organizations also offer 
information 
national aids hotline 1800342aids 1800344sida for 
spanish 1800aids889 for hearingimpaired 
